'''''Four Lions''''' (working title ''Boilerhouse'') is the debut feature film from director [[Chris Morris (satirist)|Chris Morris]] and is written by Morris, [[Sam Bain]] and [[Jesse Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://living.scotsman.com/comedy/The-prolific-writing-trio-behind.4909009.jp |title=The prolific writing trio behind Peep Show and The Thick Of It tell why they're pushing the mainstream so close to the edge |publisher=[[The Scotsman]] |accessdate=2009-07-28 |author=Jay Richardson |date=25 January 2009}}</ref> The film is a [[satire]] based on a group of four [[Islam]]ic [[Jihadi]] terrorists from the north of [[England]].

==Plot==
The plot follows four young [[Muslim]] men from the [[northern England|north of England]] who become radicalised and decide to become [[suicide attack|suicide bombers]]. Two members of the group, Omar ([[Riz Ahmed]]) and Waj ([[Kayvan Novak]]), go to a [[terrorist training camp]] in Pakistan.<ref name=Independent20100125>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/first-night-four-lions-sundance-film-festival-1877852.html |title=First Night: Four Lions, Sundance Film Festival |author=Kaleem Aftab |date=25 January 2010 |publisher=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=2010-01-27}}</ref> The other two are Barry ([[Nigel Lindsay]]), who is a [[Conversion to Islam|convert to Islam]], and Fessal (Adeel Akhtar), who tries to train crows to be bombers.<ref name=Variety>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941963.html?categoryId=31&cs=1 |title=Four Lions Review - Read Variety's Analysis Of The Movie Four Lions |author=Justin Chang |date=24 January 2010 |publisher=''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref> A fifth member, Hassan (Arsher Ali), is recruited by Barry while Omar and Waj are in Pakistan.<ref name=Independent20100125/> Fessal accidentally kills himself during a training exercise.<ref name=Independent20100125/> The film culminates in the remaining four trying to blow themselves up at the [[London Marathon]].<ref name=Observer20100124>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2010/jan/24/chris-morris-four-lions |title=Four Lions: How satirist Chris Morris fixed his eye on ideology and bombers |author=Nick Fraser |date=24 January 2010 |publisher=The Observer |accessdate=2010-02-07}}</ref>

==Production==
Morris claims to have spent three years researching this project, speaking to terrorism experts, police, the secret service, imams as well as ordinary Muslims, writing the script in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2007/nov/25/bookscomment.religion |title=The Absurd world of Martin Amis |publisher=The Observer |author=[[Chris Morris (satirist)|Chris Morris]] |date=25 November 2007 |accessdate=2009-07-26}}</ref> Morris has described the film as a "[[farce]]" which exposes the "''[[Dad's Army]]'' side to terrorism";<ref name=Independent20090106/> Warp's Deirdre Steed compares it to ''[[Spinal Tap (band)|Spinal Tap]]'' or ''[[Dr. Strangelove]]''.<ref name=Independent20090106>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/wannabe-suicide-bombers-beware-chris-morris-movie-gets-goahead-1228152.html |title=Wannabe suicide bombers beware: Chris Morris movie gets go-ahead |publisher=[[The Independent]] |author=Genevi<U+00E8>ve Roberts |date=6 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-07-26}}</ref>

The project was originally rejected by both the [[BBC]] and [[Channel 4]] as being too controversial. Morris suggested in a mass email that fans could contribute between <U+00A3>25 and <U+00A3>100 each to the production costs of the film and would appear as extras in return.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thequietus.com/articles/00535-new-chris-morris-project |title=Chris Morris announces Jihad Film/Needs money |publisher=[[The Quietus]] |author=David Moats |date=13 October 2008 |accessdate=2009-07-26}}</ref> Funding was secured in October 2008 from [[Film4 Productions|Film 4 Productions]] and [[Warp Films]], with Mark Herbert producing. Filming began in Sheffield in May 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheffieldforum.co.uk/showthread.php?t=479391&page=2|title=Chris Morris directing something on the Moor|publisher=Sheffieldforums.co.uk|accessdate=2009-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2009/07/17/set-shot-from-chris-morris-four-lions/|title=Set shot from Chris Morris' Four Lions|publisher=Bleeding Cool.com|accessdate=2009-07-26}}</ref>

==Release==
The film premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in January 2010<ref name=BBC20100125>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8478513.stm |title=Chris Morris's terrorist comedy premieres at Sundance |publisher=BBC News |date=25 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-25}}</ref> and was short-listed for the festival's World Cinema Narrative prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://festival.sundance.org/2010/press_industry/releases/2010_sundance_film_festival_announces_films_in_competition/ |title=2010 SUNDANCE FILM FESTIVAL ANNOUNCES FILMS IN COMPETITION &#124; Sundance Festival 2010 |publisher=Festival.sundance.org |date= |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref> Introducing the film's premiere Chris Morris said: <U+201C>I feel in a weird way that this is a good-hearted film. It's not a hate film, so I would hope that that aspect would come through."<ref name=EyeForFilm.co.uk>{{cite web|url=http://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/feature.php?id=774 |title=Roaring into controversy?: Chris Morris on his inspiration for suicide bomber comedy Four Lions - and why his isn't worried about the press |publisher=[[Eye For Film]] |author=Amber Wilkinson |date=17 February 2010 |accessdate=2010-02-18}}</ref> 

The UK premiere took place at the [[Bradford International Film Festival]] on 25th March 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalmediamuseum.org.uk/biff/10/film_detail.asp?filmid=8928 |title=Four Lions - Bradford International Film Festival 2010 |publisher=National Media Museum |date= |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref> and nationwide release is scheduled for 7 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2010/feb/06/four-lions-chris-morris-writers-sundance |title=Four Lions Sundance diary |publisher=The Guardian |date=06 February 2010 |accessdate=2010-02-08}}</ref>

==Reaction==
Upon its screening at Sundance, ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' and ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film extremely positive reviews, the latter describing the film as "a brilliant takedown of the imbecility of fanaticism" drawing comparisons with ''[[This Is Spinal Tap]]'' and [[The Three Stooges]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2010/01/sundance-2010-four-lions-is-scary-funny.html |title=Sundance 2010: 'Four Lions' is scary funny |publisher=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film-reviews/four-lions-film-review-1004062232.story |title=Four Lions -- Film Review |publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref> Other reactions, notably those from UK publications were more critical. The ''[[Financial Times]]'' called the film a "spectacular miss"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/3de39ace-09d6-11df-8b23-00144feabdc0.html |title=Sundance film festival |publisher=[[Financial Times]] |date=25 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref> and ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote "as a satire on terror, ''Four Lions'' seems to be a missed opportunity".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/2010/jan/25/four-lions-chris-morris |title=Chris Morris's Four Lions: a mixed dish that fails to satisfy |publisher=The Guardian |date=25 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-31}}</ref>

The UK premiere at the National Media Museum in Bradford, UK; had a warm reception from the audience and was followed by a question and answer session with Chris Morris, Jesse Armstrong, Sam Bain, three of the principal actors and two of the producers. Chris Morris stated that he doesn't find the film at all controversial and that attempting to cause controversy is, "one of the most boring things you can do".

